{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"616eabb3-b4bb-413d-b2b9-0dd7ba7019b3","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Copying the trace off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, thread-pool stats — useful to confirm the issue before collecting a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to no SDK in the container, you can download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) or use a sidecar with the SDK installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ebf3940f-0d2d-406a-9052-4066af8856c5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a knowledge/advisory question, not a code task. I'll provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":438,"requestId":"D847:E9BC6:7DD252:9170F9:69FBE995"},"id":"ae635024-e09e-4f1e-818f-94eac68f74f3","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:23:43.884Z","parentId":"b0a8871d-8544-4c83-8bac-c60fb79f9b82"}
